,"1100":"1100","about 1125":"about 1125","about 1145":"about 1145","1185":"1185","about 1124":"about 1124","1171":"1171","Chetwode, Buckinghamshire, England":"Chetwode, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Chetwode","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Chetwood  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Chatwood","meanings":["English:  see  Chetwood  ."]},{"name":"Chetwood","meanings":["English: habitational name from Chetwode in Buckinghamshire or from Cheetwood in Cheetham, Manchester (Lancashire). This placename consists of the Brittonic placename element <i>cēto-</i> ‘wood’, with an explanatory addition in Old English of <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’. The surname may also be a Shropshire variant of   Chatwin  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Chetwode was born about 1125, in Chetwode, Buckinghamshire, England, his father, John de Chetwode, was 27 and his mother, Anne, was 27. He married Joanne Roberts about 1145, in Chetwode, Buckinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1145, in his hometown, at the age of 21."},"et":{"about 1125–1145":"umbes 1125–1145","1125–1145":"1125–1145","1126–1185":"1126–1185","1145–1171":"1145–1171","1145–Male":"1145–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1126":"1126","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","about 1125":"umbes 1125","about 1145":"umbes 1145","1185":"1185","about 1124":"umbes 1124","1171":"1171","Chetwode, Buckinghamshire, England":"Chetwode, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1125–1145":"noin 1125–1145","1125–1145":"1125–1145","1126–1185":"1126–1185","1145–1171":"1145–1171","1145–Male":"1145–Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1100–Female":"1100–Kuollut","1126":"1126","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","about 1125":"noin 1125","about 1145":"noin 1145","1185":"1185","about 1124":"noin 1124","1171":"1171","Chetwode, Buckinghamshire, England":"Chetwode, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1125–1145":"environ 1125–1145","1125–1145":"1125–1145","1126–1185":"1126–1185","1145–1171":"1145–1171","1145–Male":"1145–Décédé","1100–Male":"1100–Décédé","1100–Female":"1100–Décédée","1126":"1126","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","about 1125":"environ 